Construction and renovations are today's theme here at the SFU Museum of Archaeology &amp; Ethnology and have been for several weeks now! ¬†Staff and volunteers have been busy packing and moving exhibits and artifacts. ¬†It's been a lot of work and inconvenience for everyone here, but we've managed.

And despite the Museum being closed, we continue to be active online. ¬†This week we updated the Museum's website, adding a new virtual exhibit "Beyond the Masks", about wooden masks from different parts of Africa which are part of the Museum's collection. ¬†It was curated by two student volunteers.

&nbsp;

&nbsp;

I'm a freelance archaeological illustrator who works for a variety of archaeological projects, including the √áatalh√∂y√ºk Research Project. I draw artifacts, infographics, and maps, as well as reconstruction scenes of past people, architecture, and landscapes. Becoming an archaeological illustrator was a long journey, I was an archaeologist first. I earned a B.A. in Anthropology¬† and a M.A. in Archaeology, as well as spending over 7 years as a working archaeologist, before deciding I wanted art to play a bigger role in my life. I found archaeological illustration allowed me to combine my archaeological background with art to earn a living, at the same time as fulfilling my artistic cravings. To this end I earned a professional certificate in Science illustration from the California State University, Monterey Bay and I‚Äôve been running my freelance business ever since. You can see the range of my work <a href="http://www.killackeyillustration.com/">here</a>.

I am currently on site at √áatalh√∂y√ºk, a 9000-year-old Neolithic settlement on the Anatolian plain in Turkey. Dr. Ian Hodder runs the project through Stanford University. √áatalh√∂y√ºk is known for it‚Äôs tightly packed mudbrick houses, wall paintings, and female figurines. You can find out more about the site <a href="http://www.catalhoyuk.com/">here</a>. This is my 11th season as site illustrator and the project‚Äôs 25<sup>th</sup> and final field season. As this year‚Äôs Day of Archaeology falls on a Friday, our one day off a week, I thought I would describe an average day of work here.

[caption id="attachment_27313" align="alignnone" width="2000"]<img class="wp-image-27313 size-full" src="http://www.dayofarchaeology.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/07/20170627_jpq_2756.jpg" alt="Photo of Excavation in the North Shelter at √áatalh√∂y√ºk" width="2000" height="1335" /> Excavation in the North Shelter at √áatalh√∂y√ºk. Copyright Jason Quinlan and the Catalhoyuk Research Project.[/caption]

&nbsp;

[caption id="attachment_27314" align="aligncenter" width="1000"]<img class="wp-image-27314" src="http://www.dayofarchaeology.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/07/20170721_jpq_0551.jpg" alt="Photo of me touching up an illustration of a stone female figurine in the Konya Archaeology Museum." width="1000" height="1498" /> Me last week touching up an illustration of a stone female figurine in the Konya Archaeology Museum.[/caption]

Our working day starts a 6 am and goes to 6:30 pm with a short breakfast break and a longer afternoon break when the heat peaks. I have a lot to get done this season as the project is preparing a final round of publications and this is my last chance to draw artifacts for the different specialist chapters (no artifacts can leave the country). Right now I am in the midst of drawing pottery sherds, groundstone tools, and some figurines. Each artifact is carefully measured and drawn to scale in pencil. At this stage I usually confer with the material specialist to make sure I have included all the details they are interested in, such as manufacturing marks or special views. I then ink the illustration by hand on drafting film and add finishing details such as scales and continuation lines digitally. I also work closely with the site photographer, <a href="https://jasonquinlan.com/">Jason Quinlan</a>, to make sure everything is documented properly. I sometimes even use his orthophoto models as a foundation to draw on for very complicated objects. Because there is so much to draw, I have 3 other illustrators helping me out this season: Caroline Hebron, <a href="http://www.jennieanderson.co.uk/">Jennie Anderson</a>, and Danica Mihailovic. A not insignificant portion of my time is going to management of the other illustrators, meeting with the material specialists to arrange what everyone is drawing, and archiving the finished illustrations. Below are some examples of different types of artifacts that I have drawn over the years at √áatalh√∂y√ºk.

&nbsp;

[caption id="attachment_27218" align="aligncenter" width="2562"]<img class="wp-image-27218 size-full" src="http://www.dayofarchaeology.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/07/Female_figurine_Kathryn_Killackey.jpg" alt="graphite illustration of a Neolithic stone female figurine from √áatalh√∂y√ºk" width="2562" height="2056" /> Neolithic stone female figurine excavated in 2016. Copyright Kathryn Killackey and the √áatalh√∂y√ºk Research Project.[/caption]

&nbsp;

[caption id="attachment_27220" align="alignnone" width="2550"]<img class="size-full wp-image-27220" src="http://www.dayofarchaeology.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/07/stampseals_Kathryn_Killackey.jpg" alt="Pen and ink illustration of Neolithic clay stamp seals from √áatalh√∂y√ºk " width="2550" height="3300" /> Neolithic clay stamp seals. Copyright Kathryn Killackey and the √áatalh√∂y√ºk Research Project.[/caption]

&nbsp;

[caption id="attachment_27221" align="alignnone" width="5113"]<img class="size-full wp-image-27221" src="http://www.dayofarchaeology.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/07/botanical_remains_Kathryn_Killackey.jpg" alt="Graphite illustration of Neolithic spikelet forks from √áatalh√∂y√ºk. " width="5113" height="6613" /> Neolithic botanical Remains (Cereal Spikelet Forks). Copyright Kathryn Killackey and the √áatalh√∂y√ºk ResearchProject.[/caption]

&nbsp;

[caption id="attachment_27224" align="alignnone" width="1275"]<img class="size-full wp-image-27224" src="http://www.dayofarchaeology.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/07/Bead_Typology_Kathryn_Killackey.jpg" alt="Vector illustration of Neolithic clay bead typology from √áatalh√∂y√ºk " width="1275" height="1650" /> Neolithic clay bead typology. Copyright Kathryn Killackey and the √áatalh√∂y√ºk Research Project.[/caption]

[caption id="attachment_27226" align="alignnone" width="4667"]<img class="size-full wp-image-27226" src="http://www.dayofarchaeology.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/07/pottery_Kathryn_Killackey.jpg" alt="Pen and ink illustrations of pottery sherds from √áatalh√∂y√ºk. " width="4667" height="6600" /> Neolithic pottery sherds. Copyright Kathryn Killackey and the √áatalh√∂y√ºk Research Project.[/caption]

[caption id="attachment_27228" align="alignnone" width="3237"]<img class="size-full wp-image-27228" src="http://www.dayofarchaeology.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/07/glass_Kathryn_Killackey.jpg" alt="Vector illustration of Roman glass tear catcher bottles from √áatalh√∂y√ºk" width="3237" height="4112" /> Roman glass tear catcher bottles. Copyright Kathryn Killackey and the √áatalh√∂y√ºk Research Project.[/caption]

There are currently no ongoing excavations, the last digging stopped a couple weeks ago. When there is active excavation I am sometimes called up on site to record wall paintings or other complicated features. I use sheets of clear mylar to trace off the wall paintings and then scan and digitize them. Once they are in digital form I can use my knowledge of other wall paintings on site to try and reconstruct parts of them. While I haven‚Äôt recorded any wall painting this season, I am still working on digitizing and reconstructing older recordings. Below are and example of a wall painting recording and of a architectural feature recording.

&nbsp;

&nbsp;

[caption id="attachment_27229" align="alignnone" width="2859"]<img class="size-full wp-image-27229" src="http://www.dayofarchaeology.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/07/Building_80_Wall_Painting_Kathryn_Killackey.jpg" alt="Photograph and illustration of the geometric wall painting in Building 80." width="2859" height="1522" /> My recording of Building 80‚Äôs geometric wall painting (bottom) and Jason Quinlan‚Äôs photo of the same painting (top). Copyright Kathryn Killackey, Jason Quinlan, and the √áatalh√∂y√ºk ResearchProject.[/caption]

&nbsp;

[caption id="attachment_27232" align="alignnone" width="3192"]<img class="size-full wp-image-27232" src="http://www.dayofarchaeology.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/07/Plaster_head_Kathryn_Killackey.jpg" alt="My recording of a molded plaster head with obsidian eyes and paint that adorned Building 132." width="3192" height="2147" /> My recording of a molded plaster head with obsidian eyes and paint that adorned Building 132. Copyright Kathryn Killackey and the √áatalh√∂y√ºk Research Project.[/caption]

Finally, in between drawing artifacts and reconstructing wall paintings, I have been working with the excavators and material specialists to collect information for future reconstructions. We have several publications coming up that will need reconstructions of people‚Äôs activities, architecture, and landscapes. Off site this year I will be working on a series of isometric drawings of buildings excavated since 2008. Before I leave site I need to make sure I have all the information necessary to do this, including excavation records, 3D models, building plans, and elevation drawings. I‚Äôve also started conversations with different material specialists about possible reconstructions of different activities that took place on site. This is always a time consuming process, involving many conversations and drafts to get the details and archaeological evidence represented just right. Below are some examples of an isometric drawing and some reconstructions from past publications.

[caption id="attachment_27237" align="alignnone" width="1280"]<img class="size-full wp-image-27237" src="http://www.dayofarchaeology.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/07/Catalhoyuk_Bldg.58_isometric_Killackey.jpg" alt="Isometric drawing of Building 58" width="1280" height="989" /> Isometric drawing of Building 58. Copyright Kathryn Killackey and the √áatalh√∂y√ºk Research Project.[/caption]

&nbsp;

[caption id="attachment_27239" align="alignnone" width="2852"]<img class="size-full wp-image-27239" src="http://www.dayofarchaeology.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/07/cereal_processing_Kathryn_KIllackey.jpg" alt="Graphite illustration of cereal processing in Building 49" width="2852" height="2146" /> Cereal processing in Building 49. Copyright Kathryn Killackey and the √áatalh√∂y√ºk Research Project.[/caption]

&nbsp;

[caption id="attachment_27240" align="alignnone" width="1280"]<img class="size-full wp-image-27240" src="http://www.dayofarchaeology.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/07/baby_Kathryn_KIllackey.jpg" alt="A illustration of a baby burial with grave goods from Building 49. " width="1280" height="1005" /> A baby burial with grave goods from Building 49. Copyright Kathryn Killackey and the √áatalh√∂y√ºk Research Project.[/caption]

[caption id="attachment_27241" align="alignnone" width="1280"]<img class="size-full wp-image-27241" src="http://www.dayofarchaeology.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/07/plaster_skull_burial_Kathryn_Killackey.jpg" alt="Reconstruction illustration and photograph of the plaster skull burial." width="1280" height="989" /> The plaster skull burial (left: reconstructed skeleton overlaid on Jason Quinlan‚Äôs photo, right: reconstruction of the burial at the time of internment). Copyright Kathryn Killackey, Jason Quinlan, and the √áatalh√∂y√ºk Research Project.[/caption]

My average day here at √áatalh√∂y√ºk often involves a mix of all these different tasks. I‚Äôm pretty tired by dinnertime at 6:30pm. After dinner I usually spend time at our makeshift bar with friends, escaping into a novel, or knitting to relax (I think I‚Äôll get a sweater completed this summer!). One thing I‚Äôm not doing this summer in my downtime is taking care of my daughter. She‚Äôs been with me on site for the past 4 seasons, starting when she was 3 months old. This year my husband, who is also an archaeologist, did his field work early and has her at home.

While I‚Äôm sure I have many exciting archaeological illustration adventures ahead of me, I‚Äôm going to miss √áatalh√∂y√ºk in the coming years. I‚Äôve made life-long friends here, interacted with amazing archaeology, and had the time and space to develop my illustration skills. For that I‚Äôll be forever grateful to the √áatalh√∂y√ºk Research Project and Dr. Ian Hodder.

&nbsp;

Here in Christchurch, we have the rare opportunity of being able to uncover a large proportion of the archaeology that lies beneath our city over a very short period of time. The devastating earthquakes that occurred in 2010 and 2011 caused structural damage to many properties in the Christchurch Central City and surrounds, and Underground Overground Archaeology has been on the front lines recording our city‚Äôs heritage since the occurrence of these tragic events. Christchurch has been inhabited by European settlers since 1850 and long before this time by Maori (the indigenous inhabitants of New Zealand), and we are constantly finding archaeological evidence pertaining to the daily lives of our Maori and European colonial ancestors during the repair and reconstruction of our buildings and infrastructure.

&nbsp;

On previous Days Of Archaeology, we‚Äôve offered a glimpse into our individual daily archaeological tasks and the best and brightest of our archaeological escapades can be found on our company <a href="http://blog.underoverarch.co.nz/">blog</a> and <a href="https://www.facebook.com/UnderOverArch/">Facebook</a> page. But for today‚Äôs celebrations, we thought we‚Äôd do something a little different and go for a more in-depth look at one of our central city construction sites, particularly the journey of how a single artefact is processed ‚Äì from initial onsite discovery through to storage.

&nbsp;

In the shadow of our city‚Äôs landmark (Christchurch Cathedral ‚Äì which is currently looking worse for wear), the Christchurch Convention Centre construction project will soon erect a shiny new hub of activity in the central city. The site on which the center is being built was once the location of not one, but two consecutively occupied fancy goods stores, which carried luxury commodities imported from the European continent.

&nbsp;

[caption id="attachment_27479" align="aligncenter" width="620"]<img class=" wp-image-27479" src="http://www.dayofarchaeology.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/07/P4070002-2.jpg" alt="" width="620" height="465" /> At the Convention Centre site, Angel (one of our archaeologists), monitors the excavation of a 19th century well, as it‚Äôs carefully uncovered by a mechanical excavator. Christchurch Cathedral is visible in the background. Photo: Hamish Williams.[/caption]

&nbsp;

[caption id="attachment_27493" align="aligncenter" width="417"]<img class=" wp-image-27493" src="http://www.dayofarchaeology.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/07/IMG_20170418_154625.jpg" alt="" width="417" height="340" /> Very carefully uncovered! Photo: Angel Trendafilov.[/caption]

&nbsp;

[caption id="attachment_27477" align="aligncenter" width="389"]<img class=" wp-image-27477" src="http://www.dayofarchaeology.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/07/P4030275.jpg" alt="" width="389" height="519" /> These things are often a two-man job! Photo: Hamish Williams.[/caption]

&nbsp;

The site of these luxury goods stores offers an exceptional chance to get a taste of how the upper-crust of Christchurch can been seen through their material culture. Disastrously for the proprietors (but opportunistic for us), the second store (Messrs. A. Dallas And Co. Auctioneers), suffered extensive stock loss during a fire in 1885. Much of their fire and water damaged stock was sold cheaply, the remainder was thrown out (probably on site), and the building was subsequently torn down. This kind of onsite refuse disposal was common in 19<sup>th</sup> century Christchurch, despite implementation of first council rubbish collection service in the 1860s! Go figure! An advertisement in a local newspaper describes some of the stock that was sold at auction, the most amusing, albeit confusing, of which is listed as ‚Äúhandsome walnut whatnots‚Äù. In any case, there seems to have been many a bargain to be had on auction day.

[caption id="attachment_27480" align="aligncenter" width="267"]<img class="size-full wp-image-27480" src="http://www.dayofarchaeology.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/07/Screen-Shot-2017-07-26-at-11.24.33-AM.png" alt="" width="267" height="593" /> The auction listing from an 1885 issue of the Press newspaper. Image: Press 1885.[/caption]

&nbsp;

[caption id="attachment_27474" align="aligncenter" width="498"]<img class=" wp-image-27474" src="http://www.dayofarchaeology.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/07/IMG_20170324_085612.jpg" alt="" width="498" height="282" /> Fancy some fancy finds? Photo: Angel Trendafilov.[/caption]

&nbsp;

One particularly exciting find was this glass vase which you can see Angel uncovering in a rubbish pit.

&nbsp;

[caption id="attachment_27471" align="aligncenter" width="479"]<img class=" wp-image-27471" src="http://www.dayofarchaeology.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/07/AT-in-F16.jpg" alt="" width="479" height="359" /> Glass vase being carefully excavated in the foreground. Archaeologist sold separately. Photo: Hamish Williams.[/caption]

&nbsp;

[caption id="attachment_27472" align="aligncenter" width="345"]<img class=" wp-image-27472" src="http://www.dayofarchaeology.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/07/F16-3.jpg" alt="" width="345" height="256" /> Up close and personal: Photo: Angel Trendafilov.[/caption]

&nbsp;

Having carefully removed the many fragments of this vessel from the in situ rubbish deposit, Angel transported the material from the site in bags labelled with the location and stratigraphic layer details (provenance), describing where it was found on the site. On arrival to the Underground Overground Archaeology laboratory, dirt was carefully removed with a brush, as to not unwittingly eliminate any of the fine gilt decoration on the body of the vase.

&nbsp;

[caption id="attachment_27481" align="aligncenter" width="250"]<img class=" wp-image-27481" src="http://www.dayofarchaeology.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/07/thumb_DSC_6855_1024.jpg" alt="" width="250" height="376" /> Bringing back the lustre of the dirty artefact. Photo: Jessie Garland.[/caption]

&nbsp;

Now for the fun part of every artefact analyst‚Äôs day! This artefact came back from site in over a hundred fragments - so, to determine what shape and form it originally took, we had to piece it back together, a bit like a three-dimensional historical jigsaw puzzle. Check out how we did it‚Ä¶ Note - reconstruction took a lot longer in real life. If only it were this easy!

&nbsp;

[caption id="attachment_27494" align="aligncenter" width="360"]<img class="wp-image-27494 size-full" src="http://www.dayofarchaeology.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/07/Vase-GIF.gif" alt="" width="360" height="240" /> Piece by glorious piece![/caption]

&nbsp;

Having pieced this unusual beauty back together, our artefact expert determined that it was a decorative pedestal vase, like the one featured below. Figuring out exactly what it was took a combination of guesswork, random Google searches, flipping through all of the books of the shelf, a lucky break and a tiny bit of actual expertise... It‚Äôs not as easy as you might think to figure out the specific name for something when you only know what it looks like ‚Äì on top of which, as it turns out, people didn‚Äôt use the same names for things in the 19<sup>th</sup> century as they do now (not that we‚Äôre complaining ‚Äì that moment when you do actually find the thing you‚Äôre looking for is one of the best parts of the job!).

&nbsp;

Our research determined that these lustre vases were primarily used as mantle¬†and table decorations, and had hanging cut glass prisms which would have sparkled in the sunshine. Those with one row of prisms were more common, while the double hung prisms were rarer and usually costlier (meaning, that ours was fancy enough for a fancy goods store, but maybe not <em>so</em> fancy) As far as we know, no example of a vase like this has ever been found at an 19<sup>th</sup> century archaeological site in Christchurch, so this ‚Äòhandsome‚Äô piece would definitely have fancied-up any Victorian reception room! The smoking gun in the identification of this vessel type was the tiny drilled holes in the glass and the associated copper hooks from which these prisms would have hung.

&nbsp;

[caption id="attachment_27470" align="aligncenter" width="312"]<img class="wp-image-27470 " src="http://www.dayofarchaeology.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/07/ed1.jpg" alt="" width="312" height="303" /> A fragment of the vase showing copper hooks. Photo: Chelsea Dickson[/caption]

&nbsp;

Lusters are believed to have first been produced in the British Isles and New England, and many varieties of colour and design existed in this artefact form. Red glass is thought to have been the most popular shade, making our clear glass example slightly rarer. The aesthetically pleasing nature and the variation in this artefact form makes them popular among collectors, and it has been said that it was considered the height of elegant living to own at least one pair of lusters during the Victorian era.

&nbsp;

[caption id="attachment_27492" align="aligncenter" width="558"]<img class="wp-image-27492" src="http://www.dayofarchaeology.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/07/vase.jpg" alt="" width="558" height="427" /> Left: our fragmented, but reconstructed vase. Right: a complete example of a similar style pedestal vase, otherwise known as a mantle lustre. Photo: Jessie Garland.[/caption]

&nbsp;

Having identified the artefact, one of our analysts, Jessie, catalogued and photographed the vessel, then stored it safely in acid-free tissue paper to protect the delicate gilt decoration. We often find gilt decorated ceramic vessels in our 19<sup>th</sup> century artefact assemblages, but it is less commonly seen on glassware, as the gilt doesn‚Äôt preserve as well on the smoother glass surfaces.

&nbsp;

[caption id="attachment_27489" align="aligncenter" width="616"]<img class=" wp-image-27489" src="http://www.dayofarchaeology.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/07/thumb_DSC_6893_1024.jpg" alt="" width="616" height="409" /> Jessie doing her artefact analysis thing! Note: our desks are messy because we are SO busy! Photo: Chelsea Dickson.[/caption]

&nbsp;

Lastly, storage! Our artefacts are boxed up, labelled and stored, until our associated archaeological reports are accepted by the governing heritage body in New Zealand (Heritage New Zealand). When we are given the go ahead, we can then find a new home for the artefacts, be that with the landowner, in a museum or research facility. Our clients also receive a copy of our archaeological reports so they can better understand the fantastic history of their sections of land, and these reports can also be made available to the public upon request to Heritage New Zealand.

&nbsp;

[caption id="attachment_27476" align="aligncenter" width="598"]<img class=" wp-image-27476" src="http://www.dayofarchaeology.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/07/Jessie-Garland-Kim-Bone-2013.jpg" alt="" width="598" height="397" /> Just some of the many, MANY, artefact boxes![/caption]

&nbsp;

[caption id="attachment_27473" align="aligncenter" width="541"]<img class=" wp-image-27473" src="http://www.dayofarchaeology.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/07/fancy.jpg" alt="" width="541" height="454" /> These boxes contain a couple more interesting Convention Centre artefacts that might tickle your fancy! Photo: Jessie Garland.[/caption]

&nbsp;

We hope you‚Äôve enjoyed our fancy, fun-filled archaeology day as much as we have! Until next year!

&nbsp;

[caption id="attachment_28501" align="alignnone" width="5184"]<img class="size-full wp-image-28501" src="http://www.dayofarchaeology.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/07/IMG_2321.jpg" alt="" width="5184" height="3456" /> The 2017 Avertok Archaeology Crew! Top from left to right: Laura, Emma G., John, Jacinda, Robyn, Maryssa, Bottom from left to right: Ida, Emma L.S., Kayley, Deirdre.[/caption]

Checking in from Hopedale, Nunatsiavut, this is Ida Semigak, an archaeology summer student with the Avertok Archaeology Project. The Avertok Archaeology Project is part of the larger Tradition &amp; Transition: PiusituKaujuit Asianguvalliajuillu project, which is a partnership between Memorial University in Newfoundland and the Nunatsiavut Government. Avertok is the name of the original Inuit settlement where Hopedale is located. It means "a place of whales." The project started when the Hopedale community asked Dr. Lisa Rankin from Memorial University to conduct archaeological research in the area. John Piercy and I have been hired as summer students to work on various aspects of the research.

We begin every day at the Moravian Mission, where we have set up our archaeology lab in the Mission House. The Hopedale Mission was established in 1782, and the building is the earliest surviving Moravian structure on the Labrador coast. The building was completed between 1850-1861. We organize, clean, and catalog artifacts with archaeologists Dr. Laura Kelvin and Emma Gilheany. The building is very cold, but John particularly enjoys cleaning the nails and metals recovered from site. I enjoy cleaning and examining the ceramics. Some times we have visitors in the lab like cruise participants and the kids from the Hopedale literacy camp. We give them tours of the lab and tell them about what we do in the lab.

[caption id="attachment_28491" align="alignnone" width="5184"]<img class="size-full wp-image-28491" src="http://www.dayofarchaeology.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/07/IMG_2078.jpg" alt="" width="5184" height="3456" /> Doing an "archaeological survey" with the kids from the literacy camp. They found a lot of "artifacts" (toys and candy).[/caption]

&nbsp;

[caption id="attachment_28490" align="alignnone" width="5184"]<img class="size-full wp-image-28490" src="http://www.dayofarchaeology.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/07/IMG_2024.jpg" alt="" width="5184" height="3456" /> Dr. Kelvin showing visitors from a cruise ship artifacts in the lab. Photo Credit: Rosie Edmunds.[/caption]

&nbsp;

[caption id="attachment_28485" align="alignnone" width="4156"]<img class="size-full wp-image-28485" src="http://www.dayofarchaeology.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/07/IMG_1707.jpg" alt="" width="4156" height="2770" /> A soap stone artifact found this season at the Old Hopedale site. Photo Credit: Laura Kelvin.[/caption]

This summer we have been looking at archival photos from the past that show what Hopedale used to look like. We have been taking photos and videos of these same spots around town to see what has changed.

&nbsp;

[caption id="attachment_28503" align="alignnone" width="2800"]<img class="size-full wp-image-28503" src="http://www.dayofarchaeology.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/07/mission2.jpg" alt="" width="2800" height="2800" /> Then and Now: The Moravian Mission 1886 (top) and 2017 (bottom) . Photo Credit: The Rooms Archives A7. 103, Laura Kelvin.[/caption]

[caption id="attachment_28502" align="alignnone" width="2800"]<img class="size-full wp-image-28502" src="http://www.dayofarchaeology.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/07/mission1.jpg" alt="" width="2800" height="2800" /> Then and Now: Hopedale 1930 (top) and 2017 (bottom). Photo Credit: The Rooms Archive VA 110-67.2, Ida Semigak.[/caption]

We sometimes spend our days digging in town at the Old Hopedale site or at the nearby site of Karmakulluk being excavated by Jacinda. Emma Lewis-Sing, Robyn Fleming, and Deirdre Elliot trained us in excavation techniques. I really like digging for artifacts! For example, yesterday I found a piece of wood with a hole where a nail would have been decades ago.

&nbsp;

[caption id="attachment_28500" align="alignnone" width="5184"]<img class="size-full wp-image-28500" src="http://www.dayofarchaeology.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/07/IMG_2300.jpg" alt="" width="5184" height="3456" /> Ida working at Karmakulluk. Photo Credit: Laura Kelvin.[/caption]

[caption id="attachment_28497" align="alignnone" width="5184"]<img class="size-full wp-image-28497" src="http://www.dayofarchaeology.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/07/IMG_2295.jpg" alt="" width="5184" height="3456" /> John digging at Karmakulluk. Photo Credit: Ida Semigak.[/caption]

&nbsp;

[caption id="attachment_28496" align="alignnone" width="5184"]<img class="size-full wp-image-28496" src="http://www.dayofarchaeology.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/07/IMG_2253.jpg" alt="" width="5184" height="3456" /> Karmakulluk. Photo Credit: Ida Semigak.[/caption]

Dr. Kelvin, John, and I are also interviewing community members to find out more about artifacts and traditional culture. Two of the interviews we have conducted dealt with traditional Inuit kayak-making. We are currently putting together a video, which will be posted to our YouTube page, showing the interviews. The video will also feature the cardboard kayak we made for the Rhubarb Festival‚Äôs cardboard boat race. Our kayak came in second place! In addition to interviewing community members, we have also been interviewing other members of the archaeology team.

In the last three weeks, I have enjoyed working with the archaeologists, going to the Karmakulluk site, and finding artifacts. Interviewing community members about kayak-making made John interested in helping make a kayak in the near future.

[caption id="attachment_28494" align="alignnone" width="5184"]<img class="size-full wp-image-28494" src="http://www.dayofarchaeology.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/07/IMG_2243.jpg" alt="" width="5184" height="3456" /> Ross Flowers showing Laura and John the sealskin kayak he made. Photo Credit: Ida Semigak.[/caption]

